A commit saves your staged changes into Git history.


It records:

  what changed

  when it changed

  who changed it

  a message explaining the change


We commit so we can save versions of our project.

This helps because you can:

  look back at old changes

  understand what you did

  go back to an older version if something breaks

(Oh to add to the git repo do git add ____)


Commit the file

  git commit -m "Add index page"

To see past comits do:

  git log















